  "id": "019d350f-5502-7591-9e95-d3ae759ab43d",
  "content": "# Multi-Spoke Phase 3: Autonomous Spokes - Decision Record (2026-03-28)\n\n## What: Autonomous spoke lifecycle with status reporting, auto-prune, permission hardening, telemetry, and dashboard resource monitoring.\n\n## Key Design Decisions:\n1. Status reporting uses corvia_write for key transitions only (starting, mcp-connected, claude-starting, completed, failed) to avoid knowledge base pollution. Intermediate steps (cloning, branch-setup) are logged to stdout only.\n2. Permission hardening via settings.json allow/deny lists. Removed env and xargs from allow-list after security review found they bypass docker deny rule. wget added to deny list.\n3. Auto-prune uses container creation time (not exit time) because Docker list API doesn't expose FinishedAt. Documented limitation. Default 1h threshold with 5min poll interval.\n4. Credential validation is offline (jq check for token presence in .credentials.json) not a live API call. Previous design called real Claude API which burned tokens on every spoke start.\n5. Docker stats (CPU%, memory) added to dashboard. CPU formula includes online_cpus multiplier matching docker stats CLI. Stats queries have 5s timeout per container.\n6. MCP config uses jq for JSON construction instead of string concatenation to prevent injection via special characters in URL/token.\n7. Telemetry span constants defined in corvia-telemetry but used as inline literals in info_span! calls due to tracing macro limitation requiring string literals.\n\n## Review Findings Worth Remembering:\n- env command in Bash allow-list is dangerous: `env docker ps` bypasses docker deny rule\n- Docker container stats API with stream=false can hang indefinitely without timeout\n- SpokeProvisioner should be reused in background loops, not recreated per tick\n- Container name must be sanitized before interpolating into raw HTTP requests to Docker socket",
  "source_version": "mcp",
  "scope_id": "corvia",
